text: ProTip about movies adapted from books: Always watch the movie first.  If you read the book first, you will be disappointed with the movie. You will see all the things that were left out or cut, and you will hate it for those omissions. You will notice all of the parts that were changed, and you will be blinded by anger.  And in doing so, you could be missing out on a really good film.  Going the other way - start with movie and then read the book - results in you being able to appreciate both stories. You will like the movie (assuming it was good in the first place), but you will also like all of the extra and different stuff you get from the book.  So if you have already read the book, I am sorry, you probably won't be able to enjoy the movie. But if you haven't read the book, wait to see the film first.

text: So many questions here...  1. Who or what is being carted off in the medivac at :40? 2. The openings on the ship are different. At the bottom of the ship people enter the ship through a triangular opening. At :56 at what seems to be the top of the ship the opening is square. On a certain level the crew is standing in a rectangular room that shifts their reality from standing on the floor as we would on earth, the next instant the crew is standing on the ceiling. This shifts back to the first instance as they put the birdcage down and the rest of the story continues.  3. Gravity does not exist in the ships interior vertical space. There is gravity on level where they see the rectangular opening.  4. At 1:20, when Amy Adams touched the rectangular panel did she expose herself to contamination. Is she morphing into something as the movie goes on? We see other instances of her shaking as the trailer continues.  5. At 2:14, what is shaking the shelter? 6. At 2:19, are we seeing helicopters being shot at? 7. In another trailer there is a news blip that millions of people have died and eastern Asia has been cut off from civilization... Is this an end of the world movie?

text: Spoiler Alert: Seek and find the source novella, "Story of Your Life" by Ted Chiang. It isn't on-line, as far as I can tell. He hasn't written/published much but what he has is pretty d'd good for the sci-fi genre. Still, what gets "lost in adaptation" is sheer conjecture. Best example I can think of is "The Day the Earth Stood Still," the original of which is a bona fide classic that still took material liberties with the source story, Harry Bates' "Farewell To the Master," which IS on-line and features among the best closing scenes and lines in the genre.

text: THis entire movie is based on a flawed principal. An alien species able to traverse interstellar distances and with superior technology would not deal in such a difficult and clandestine fashion. They wouldn't have issues communicating or wait for humans to make every move. The aliens in this movie act retarded. Mostly though this film reinforces the American notion that 'the other' is so vastly different that communication and understanding is near impossible. Aliens with these capabilities would not need a person to hold up a white board and teach them the English alphabet. They'd just link to the net and learn it before they even set foot on the planet. We've seen this movie in different forms over and over and over. It been lame for a decade now.Ôªø

text: The movie is supposed to be based on Ted Chiang's, Story of your life. Which is considered a Science fiction high Art. There are no guns fired and no space wars. The novella itself explores how language may affect our perception of world, determinism, causality, and arrow of time itself. The aliens come in to provide a varied perspective to the narrator of how they perceive the  world, which she does by learning their written language. I hope they stick to the novella which in my opinion is work of an art. It's freely available here https://mathisgasser.files.wordpress.com/2014/12/ted-chiang_story-of-your-life_2000.pdf

text: To all the people saying how come these super intelligent, intergalactic travellers can't speak to us?! - you totally lack both imagination and an understanding of how fundamentally language shapes thought.   If, say, their language contains much, much more information in each "syllable" than our languages, and if the order of their syllables affects the meaning of the surrounding 10 or 100 or 10.000 syllables, unlike our comparatively simple syntax, and this is how they are used to communicating ‚Äì then it would be a real struggle for them step down to our level. It would be like us learning to communicate with a species who only "talks" via pheromones or something. English (or any other human language) would be a very sub-optimal system of communication for two super-intelligent beings.  Moreover, for a super intelligent being to "present" itself to us, they would have to attempt to teach us their language, because that's how their thoughts are "encoded". Imagine trying to translate a poem into pheromones. It would take time.

text: Heptapod B: Language of Gestalts"Story of Your Life" proceeds contrapuntally, alternating between two storylines from the life of Louise Banks, a linguistics professor. Its characters are all racially unmarked. The first storyline recounts, in no particular chronological order, episodes from Louise's sometimes rocky relationship with her daughter, who we soon learn has died at age twenty-five in a rock-climbing accident. The second focuses on Louise and her partner Gary, a physicist and eventually the father of her daughter, both of whom are commissioned by the US military to learn the language of a race of aliens, which Gary calls "heptapods" on account of their seven limbs.   The two cultures suffuse both storylines. In regard to Louise's daughter's choice of profession, it becomes an intergenerational agon:  ...after graduation, you'll be heading for a job as a financial analyst. I won't understand what you do there, I won't even understand your fascination with money ... I would prefer it if you'd pursue something without regard for its monetary rewards, but I'll have no complaints. My own mother could never understand why I couldn't just be a high school English teacher. You'll do what makes you happy, and that'll be all I ask for. (112-3)¬†Even as Louise offers the opposite of the pragmatic emphasis that leads to Asian American occupational segregation, the juxtaposition of "financial analyst" to "English teacher" creates a contrast drawn in no small part from a post-1965 modality of the two cultures conflict.  The second storyline engages the rigorous scientific description and extrapolation of "hard" SF, focusing occasionally on principles from physics, but mainly on techniques in linguistics for "monolingual discovery," or the learning of a language between subjects who do not share a mediating language. The story thus thematizes the two cultures as an opposition between the "soft" and "hard" sciences. Along these lines, despite Louise's practice of scientific linguistics, she is coded as being on the other side of a cultural divide from the "hard" science of physics. At one point, Gary confesses to her that he had given up trying to learn Heptapod: "I'm just no good at languages." To which she replies, "I suppose that's fair; I have to admit, I've given up on trying to learn the mathematics" (124). In regard to genre, Chiang's choice of linguistics as the focus of a "hard" SF story is an unusual one, since the field is, both within and outside of SF circles, stereotyped as a "soft" science. "Hard" SF is concerned with "the form of imaginative literature that uses either established or carefully extrapolated science as its backbone."44 What makes Chiang's treatment of linguistics align with "hard" SF is the rigor and intricacy with which he develops Heptapod B, as well as the laws of physics he uses to analogize certain aspects of it.45 Chiang's generic revision of the "soft" SF of linguistics as a "hard" SF extrapolation is one indication of his overarching concern with achieving a formal resolution to the two cultures conflict.46 Indeed, the very title of the story‚Äî"Story of Your Life"‚Äîcasts everything that follows in this light by gesturing at the essence of the liberal arts.   The heptapod storyline becomes a vehicle for two thought experiments. The first posits a time-symmetrical language whose users possess a "simultaneous," as opposed to "sequential," consciousness that perceives all points in time at once, past, present, and future: a mode of consciousness appropriate to what philosophers of science call "block time" or the "block universe theory." A version of this theory is presented by the Time Traveller in H. G. Wells's The Time Machine: "Really this is what is meant by the Fourth Dimension, though some people who talk about the Fourth Dimension do not know they mean it. It is only another way of looking at Time. There is no difference between time and any of the three dimensions of Space except that our consciousness moves along it."47 As we will see, this theory is crucial to the story's postracial aesthetics.   The second thought experiment considers how this language might affect a sequential human consciousness vis-√†-vis the theory of linguistic relativity. Also known as the Sapir-Whorf hypothesis, this theory speculates that "The structure and lexicon of one's language influences how one perceives and conceptualizes the world, and they do so in a systematic way."48 "Story of Your Life" thus develops one of the prevailing interests in Chiang's work, the linguistic mediation of scientific reason and reality. In "The Evolution of Human Science," human scientists must decide how to interpret the impenetrable scientific research produced by super-intelligent "metahumans," so they begin developing techniques of "textual hermeneutics." "Seventy-Two Letters" poses the theory that "there [is] a lexical universe as well as a physical one, and bringing an object together with a compatible name [causes] the latent potentialities of both to be realized."49 The narrator of "The Truth of Fact, The Truth of Feeling" observes, "We don't normally think of it as such, but writing is a technology, which means that a literate person is someone whose thought processes are technologically mediated. We became cognitive cyborgs as soon as we became fluent readers, and the consequences of that were profound."50 As we will see below, "Understand" centers on the novum of a language of gestalts and is in many ways an apprentice work to "Story of Your Life." For Chiang, the technologization of language is often a conduit for considerations of difference: intergenerational, racial, professional, etc.51   Upon arrival, the heptapods themselves remain in orbit, but they deploy one hundred and twelve wall-sized "looking glasses" to various sites on Earth to serve as two-way videoconferencing screens. Louise and Gary begin holding virtual meetings with the heptapods, who are patient and cooperative in teaching them their spoken and written languages, which Louise designates Heptapod A and B, respectively. These languages, Louise soon comes to realize, are completely separate: B is not "glottographic" like human writing, because it "conveys meaning without reference to speech" (108). Faced with the problem of how to categorize Heptapod B, Louise rejects the categories of logograms and ideograms, which appear to be obvious analogues. She disqualifies "logogram" because it implies a corresponding spoken word, and "ideogram" for the somewhat cryptic reason of "how it had been used in the past" (111). She settles on "semagrams," since the sentences of Heptapod B operate according to their own grammar and syntax. They look "almost like mandalas," she explains: the large, intricate, circular images representing the totality of the universe in Buddhist cosmology:  When a Heptapod B sentence grew fairly sizable, its visual impact was remarkable. If I wasn't trying to decipher it, the writing looked like fanciful praying mantids¬†drawn in a cursive style, all clinging to each other to form an Escheresque lattice, each slightly different in its stance. And the biggest sentences had an effect similar to that of psychedelic posters: sometimes eye-watering, sometimes hypnotic. (112)

text: Just saw the movie and it was great and very thought provoking. However, I'm no linguist, but I'd imagine learning/translating a totally alien language would be next to impossible, especially in such a short span of time. Language is shaped by culture and it may not be possible to learn much of the alien language without understanding their culture and history first, especially for a written language. Even learning simple greetings would be extremely difficult since that's also entrenched in culture and history. In the movie, they taught and learned from the aliens using gestures, pictures, and movements, but I'm not sure if that's enough. At the very least it'd take years.

text: I just saw this last night and I CANNOT for the life of me understand the people calling it boring and stupid. Do you not have any imagination?? Right away I was drawn in, it started off suspenseful and spooky. I wasn't looking for explosions and war and mindless violence. Is that what you need to be entertained? Gratuitous violence to stimulate your senses? My fianc√© and I have VERY different taste in movies. He thought Donnie Darko was boring and stupid and it's one of my favorites. Even he described the movie ending as epic. It is mind blowing. I went in knowing there was gonna be some kind of twist ending and I was really trying to figure it out and I wouldn't have seen that from a mile away. It's thoughtful and emotional and tugs at your heartstrings. And if it didn't well then that's probably because you are just desensitized by all the violence you yearn for in movies

text: Spoilers!!!!!!!!  for those who have seen the movie but still do not understand and are still very confused with the flashbacks.       the main character, Amy adams, is a psychic (she has visions of future events).  those weren't flashbacks in the movie, they were flashforwards of what will happen in her life.  this whole movie takes place before her daughter was even born. so yes sadly, she has not physically been through the process of grieving her daughter's death.  she's only experienced them through visions of her future.  so yes her daughter will still die in the future üò≠.  this movie had me confused the whole time with all those frequent flashbacks.  I later figured out that they were actually her visions of the future.  when i realized this, I was pleasantly shocked!!!  haven't experienced this kind of a twisted ending since "the sixth sense" and "the others".  we need more movies like this!!!

text: I saw Arrival and unlike some (maybe most) commenters, I didn't like to movie.  Although the performances were believable along with the plot, I felt that from the alternate possible scenario and end of humanity depicted in the last few clips in several trailers for the movie, duped me into watching the movie.  I totally get how her knowing the future in her mind, time was not linear in the sense of taking that future knowledge and applying it to their present dilemma to change the outcome of the present and thus alter the future (in the case of those alien vs. human conflicts in the trailers which never actually happen in the movie!!).   So, no for me, the shallow concept didn't fly.  And I was left feeling duped just like after seeing "The Blair Witch Project".   My philosophical entertainment isn't so easily satiated by an old cliche with a new twist and a big name Hollywood star carrying the success of the movie on her back.  Reminds me of Margot Robbie saving Suicide Squad - raising it to box of glory on her looks and her crazily awesome performance of Harley Quinn.  BTW, no one else really mattered in that film.  Not even my boy, Will Smith!

text: I saw this movie on the weekend and really enjoyed it. Those expecting a fast paced action movie probably won't like it. This movie is more about building tension and character development. Elements of war are undertones throughout the movie, but that's not what the movie is about despite the trailer conveying that idea. Every scene is a visual masterpiece, well acted, and the soundtrack does a really good job at conveying emotion. There is a plot twist at the end that is a bit of a mind bender, but is very subtle in the sense that it really isn't explained to you. You have to pay attention to the whole film and look for clues throughout. Only complaints I have are that some characters were one-dimensional and the bits with the daughter were really cheesy. But, overall I would rate that with Ex Machina and 10 Cloverfield Lane as great recent sci-fi movies.  Definitely watch this one in theaters if you are interested in it at all.

text: this is important to note going into the movie: if you're looking for an intense alien landing on Earth thrill then you're not going to get that. The movie was very enjoyable as a food for thought kind of movie that sort of tells you to look at yourself and people as a whole and how we do things and why we do them and all that other shit. It's the kind of movie that is supposed to just leave you in a wondering mindset rather than a oh what a cool alien movie. In the end it's not even that much about the aliens than it is about what they are trying to communicate to one person over the course of the whole movie, which is really just about a single question. I won't say more else I might get into spoilers. 7/10 because it was a slight underwhelming and especially after watching the trailer again i really feel like they advertised it as more of a thriller and an action-packed movie, they basically used every cool looking danger-ish scene and the rest of the movie moves quite slow. but dont get me wrong, it's still a pretty dope movie

text: SPOILER ALERT  excellent movie but huge time paradox problem. When she sees herself speaking to the chinese leader in th future, then repeats what he said to her, to her past self. Its a bootstrap paradox. She must tell her past self what she heard in the future, but in order to for her future self to hear those words from the chinese man, her past self has to tell those words to the chinese man. it becomes a time loop. The future she remembers is caused by the words she said in the past. Back and forth.

text: It's really lame. I know I don't expect another Human vs Alien action movie, but this feels like they just found a 10 pages 'peaceful'  alien movie script on trashcan and decided to roll with it.  *MILD SPOILER RANT*    Hollywood once again put dumbass 'smart' alien. Srsly, the idea of an advanced & intelligent Alien who can write and want to unify people with a language and decided to go to earth without knowing alphabet is just beyond me. The decoding process of the totally alien language with the speed of CSI' DNA test is too cheesy too.  Boy, I miss the time when I can enjoy movies without thinking about the plot holes.   Beside, I'm sick with this repetitive shit producers put on movies :  - Generic actors that you can expect what the movie will end up with? Check. - Protagonist is regular citizen and is an expert at something? Check. - Protagonist gets taken by the military with a chopper within 15 mins? Check. - Scenes that actually mean for viewers to feel the intense of the situation, but ended up unnecessarily long? Double Check. - Military people that act like a kid losing an argument at 9Gag? No real harm done, but still throwing a tantrum anyway? Triple Check.  My favorite part is that people bragging their IQ score for liking a movie they thought have deep meaning.

text: If you're looking for light saber fights and invading aliens, this  is not the sci fi movie for you. Arrival is "serious" sci fi, which is  to say it's  cerebral and philosophical vs. action and special effects.   It reminded me of the Jodie Foster movie Contact, with some   Interstellar thrown in. Contact and Interstellar were better movies in  my view.  Arrival is as much statement on human behavior and inherent  paranoia of individuals and governments as it is about mysterious aliens stopping by the say hello.   How they learn to talk to the aliens is not very convincing and the  movie lacks any real character development and intentionally confusing  it seemed. Think  Interstellar without anything interesting ever  happening. What ever this movie was trying to impart on the viewer, I  missed it. I guess "don't sweat it" is the message cuz time is not  linear... Was she traveling through time? Where the aliens doing it or  was she having visions of past and future on her own? You're left with  far more questions than answers and the answers not very satisfying. The  acting, visuals, and music, are first rate, and without that, would  have been difficult to watch. B-  If you enjoyed  Interstellar and Contact, you'll probably enjoy Arrival,

text: TBH, in reality, language barriers would be almost non-existent by the time an alien species is able to find and land on Earth (unless they just land on it by accident).  The reason is really quite simple. We have been sending out waves from our radios and tvs for decades and any alien species would come into contact with our broadcasting long before they discover us. Through this they would figure out where we are and as such they would have literally decades to decipher our languages to a level that is at least workable, regardless of what means they personally communicate with. So long as they have a means to manipulate the world and travel large distances they have the ability to create a medium to communicate with us and will be capable of doing so by the time they arrive.

text: For those who didn't enjoy this film, it's not because it was "terrible," it's just that it wasn't your cup of tea. It is clear that you didn't understand the point or message behind the movie because you couldn't even understand the goddamn trailer.   If you want movies with only men punching one another, and a guy with a big ass gun, watch a sci-fi film that took less thought and was made for the brainless. text: I have three things to say : 1. What an incredible movie. Truly refreshing alien themed film. 2.  Todays trailers suck balls. Trailer people dont know how to make trailers anymore. They completely ruin the film experience by spoiling too much and/or dont do justice to the film. They should be kept short and intriguing enough.  3. I dont watch trailers to films anymore. Trust me. I watched this movie before I'd seen anything about it. No trailers no nothing. I can tell you now the experience was completely different. From seeing the aliens for the first time, to slowly understanding the plot line as the characters do, to seeing their language signs for the first time not knowing what to expect. People who watched the trailer would already know all these things. Its not the same experience. Trust me . Dont watch trailers anymore guys. ( At least for these sort of genres like horror/ mystery/ thriller..comedy and romance? myeh trailers dont ruin those much)

Not because it was bad, it was the complete opposite. This movie deserves to be watched on a big screen with loud speakers so you get fully engaged and not distracted by a "chicken or pasta" question. It's a one shot movie like Memento or Inception, like them or not you are not able to watch them again. Long story short: Watch it on your TV, put your phone in airplane mode, cancel everything for the next two hours and thank me later.

text: I enjoyed the film. A bit very repetitive and slow with the scenes of the circles probably to get you to feel what the linguists is feeling and fed up with as well. But I love how people on here are saying they weren‚Äôt confused about the movie as if seeking assurance and acknowledgment that  they are intelligent üòÇ. It‚Äôs not about weather you understood it or not because it can be very subjective and not trying to be one meaning for all but leaving room for your imagination of how you want to perceive the film. Yes it has one goal, to explain or imply that it‚Äôs about communication and altering or not being able to alter, events that will happen because it‚Äôs life and life happens in mysterious ways that we as humans still don‚Äôt not understand but like to believe that we have the power to do so and that anything we do can affect and cause a chain reaction and repercussions. The movie was clear what it wants you to perceive but leaves room for you to make up your own mind. It doesn‚Äôt want you to exactly know what it‚Äôs hinting at. That‚Äôs up to the vision of the creator/writer and their take. Everyone has a different take on life and meaning and understandings and ultimately in the way we communicate. Just like the title of movie can Imply and be a deep communication to us the importance of the arrival of Louis daughter is to her more than her death (departure). The movie does not clearly reveal or hint at ‚Äútime travel‚Äù or understanding the future past or present for that matter but left to the viewer to interpret what it‚Äôs revealing just as the aliens are trying and wanting humans to do. Maybe that is the artistic metaphor and deep meaning of the movie and it‚Äôs goal. To have the viewers try to decipher the film as the characters. If the movie was sooo clear as many on here state it was and feel they are sooo intelligent, then why did you come to this section in commentary and look up videos of ‚Äúending explained‚Äù in the first place? I bet it was to reassure themselves because they second guessed the endings meanings. Because the film was not clear and it was intentional in the first place!!! But that‚Äôs just my opinion. I feel the overall movies message was communication within humanity is essential. We may all be divided by location but we should not be with our understanding, our ideals, morals. How our initial impulse is to mistrust anything as not have hope or the right impulse to understand...come together. While humans themselves as intelligent as we are and have the gift to be able to be and mend many problems are so incompetent in the end and will be instrumental in the cause of the end of us and the world. After all, we are only humans.Just as Louis sketches the word and is significant. How easy it is for us but hard we make it to come together as one in a desperate time and put our differences aside and save us especially from ourselves.

text: after seeing the movie I wanted to see people‚Äôs discussions and their take in the movies ending and meaning. I understood the movie and analyzed it before reading and I‚Äôm glad I did. It was fun seeing people‚Äôs take on it. I also learned three things I didn‚Äôt notice or know in the movie. Like the alien ship inspired by the rectangle ship in Stanley Kubricks alien film. And I didn‚Äôt analyze certain things in the film that were hidden meanings or short reveals inspired by things like the tentacles of the aliens being the star symbol for power, communication etc and the ink circles being like the snake circle symbol about life and death and the ships shape being like an eye concave/convex or like a contact lens possibly implying ‚Äúeye‚Äù as in open your eyes humans...and then open your minds then open your hearts. Either that was intentional and being an artistic approach or in just over analyzing

text: I just watched this movie and found it really underwhelming. The first hour was really cool and I was pretty hooked on the whole concept of establishing communication with the aliens, but the second half was extremely boring. I figured out the plot twist a long time before it happened; hints were being dropped left and right. A good plot twist is one that catches you off guard, or at least isn't so obvious that it erases any other possible scenarios from your mind. But this twist was so obvious that if you didn't figure it out a half hour before the movie executed it, you just weren't paying attention. Seriously, the entire second half was just "yea saw that coming... uh huh... yep knew it". By time the twist actually happened I was already over it, which was disappointing because the first half had me really excited. I just feel it was made too obvious.   To the guy in the comments who compared this to Interstellar, predictability is what separates them and makes Interstellar a much better movie, not necessarily the visuals. Anybody who tells you they saw the Interstellar plot twist coming is a liar. Much better execution there. Just my opinion.

text: The movie questions our linear concept of time, this business of starting from the beginning and stopping at the end. But what if time could be bent, shaped, moulded, to fit our purpose? If we could make choices about the present from the future and feel the impact of future choices in the present? This amorphous, flexible nature of time.  Hence, in keeping with this theme, the movie doesn't have a strictly linear sequence of events - all are beautifully and complexly juxtaposed, one on the other.  Recognising this requires paying careful attention, as when Louise says to Ian, "I just realised why my husband left me," even though she was speaking to the one who would become that husband; or while in a trance from the future told her daughter (who was yet unborn) that "her father left because she told him what he wasn't ready to hear"; or when Louise averts a global war due to insights she gained from the future with her now fully-formed ability for time-bending, and many such scenarios peppered throughout this captivating movie.  She doesn't always have the answers even in the future and many times has to fill these blank spaces with updated knowledge from the present; such instances as the identity of her husband, providing her daughter with the answer to a Science question, and how she came about the ability to gain insights from the future. The future gains from the present just as equally as the present profits from the future. It isn't one way, linear; it's cyclical.  Then the denouement, when Louise asks Ian, if knowing how his life will play out, he would change anything. The zinger of a question that makes us consider the security that our linear universe provides - the protection that comes from not knowing, free from the nerve-wracking pressure of deciding present and future fates.
author: Akinlabi Omo-Oso

We can only go with the information we‚Äôre given, so giving bad information to the audience is a cheap and childish way to create a ‚Äútwist‚Äù in the plot.

text: I literally watch this because of the reviews and this comment section. And here is my take on this the movie itself is pretty good and is definitely very different and unique from your typical alien movies. I don't find this movies complicated at all, its just a little bit boring at first and if you don't understand this movie you probably won't enjoy it so i recommend trying to focus at the beginning of the movie.  Cinematography 8.5/10 - it has a very good visual effect.  Storyline 8/10 - you have to be open minded and you will starting to get it near the ending.  Acting 9.5/10 - i mean it's jeremy runner what can i say.  Realistic 9/10 - well it definitely has some real science in there and it realistically depicted what an alien might actually be like.  Overall 8/10 - i love movies like this it takes on a different approach and i love creativity no none cliche storyline that is illogical and make you go like 'this is stupidity'. A handful of movies try to go towards a different approach but it doesn't always end up like this.

It's not about the Aliens, it's about us, mankind, our perceptions, how we view ourselves and deal with each other. Arrival along with Ryan Eslinger's 2018 film UFO are two of the best cinematic representations of what first contact could look like. Visually stunning with a phenomenal performance from Amy Adams, a great supporting cast, and a smart script make Arrival a not to miss film for all Science Fiction fans!

text: For me this is one of the dumbest sci-fi films ever - all about communicating with octopus shaped aliens that float about in smoky mist, complete with squirted octopus ink writing that only one person in the story can decipher. To start with it's 'dumb' because the alien egg-shaped ship opens its door and the dumb people in the story, without a second thought, climb aboard to explore regardless of any imagined danger. There's that patronising aspect, often sugaring USA film scripts, in having a female front-up as the one who knows and understands with her womanly intuition what to do with ugly alien octopuses that wave tentacles about and squirt ink. I clicked through the dvd rapidly just to get the gist and have the film over and done with. No problem as I bought the dvd secured unused in its cellophane wrapper for ¬£3 in a charity shop in the UK. Glad, at least, I helped charity. I mean - honestly - don't bother with this movie. Can't understand how others commenting here appear to rate this rubbish so highly.
